# Week 6 Lab Activity

# DevOps

---

## Learning Outcomes

In this lab activity, you’ll learn how to develop a DevOps pipeline that tests code, packages it into a Docker container, and evolves it into a live cloud service. Then, you will perform an incremental updates and automatically redeploy the application. At the end of this exercise, you should be able to:

1. Explain how the DevOps pipeline works.  
2. Demonstrate the configuration of DevOps pipeline.

## Step 1: The Construction Phase (Local)

1. We start with a basic Node.js application that is a simple to-do-list application. Below is a brief explanation of the application:  
   

| index.js (Backend): Express server that provides REST API endpoints (/api/todos) Serves static files from the public folder via app.use(express.static('public')) (line 11\) Handles data persistence to todos.json app.js (Frontend): Browser JavaScript served by index.js to clients Makes HTTP requests to the API endpoints: GET /api/todos to fetch todos POST /api/todos to add todos PUT /api/todos/:id to toggle completion DELETE /api/todos/:id to delete todos Handles DOM manipulation and user interactions Flow: When users visit the server, index.js serves app.js to their browser, which then communicates back with index.js via API calls to manage todo items. |
| :---- |

   

2. Fork and clone the to-do-list web application from this GitHub repository: [https://github.com/cragkhit/simple-todo-list](https://github.com/cragkhit/simple-todo-list).  
3. Inspect the code and the tests by looking at [index.js](http://index.js) (backend), public/app.js (front-end), and \_\_tests\_\_/[app.test.js](http://app.test.js) (tests).   
4. Run the app by issuing the following commands:

## Step 2: Packaging the App using Docker (Local)

10. Next, we will learn about packaging our application using Docker.  
    

| *What is Docker?* Think of Docker as a standardized shipping container for your software. In the past, moving code from a developer's laptop to a production server was like trying to transport goods; items would break or go missing because the environments were different (the "it works on my machine" problem).  Docker packages your application along with every single thing it needs to run, e.g., libraries, settings, and dependencies, into a single, lightweight container.  This ensures that the software behaves identically whether it’s sitting on your computer, a teammate's machine, or a cloud server, making the process of software evolution much more predictable and reliable. |
| :---- |

    

11. After you have fixed the bug, manually package the app by creating a Dockerfile with the content shown below:  
    

| \# Use Node.js 18 Alpine as base image (lightweight) FROM node:18-alpine \# Set working directory inside the container WORKDIR /app \# Copy package.json and package-lock.json COPY package\*.json ./ \# Install dependencies RUN npm install \# Copy all application files to the container COPY . . \# Expose port 3000 (Node.js app port) EXPOSE 3000 \# Start the application CMD \["node", "index.js"\] |
| :---- |

    

12. Start Docker Desktop. Then, run the following command and ensure it starts.  
    

| docker build \-t w6-lab-app . |
| :---- |

    

13. You should see the Docker image appears in your Docker Desktop.  
    ![][image3]  
14. Run the image using the command below.  
    

| docker run \-p 8080:3000 w6-lab-app |
| :---- |

    

15. You’ll see that the container is now active.  
    ![][image4]  
16. Visit your application again at [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080). You should see the same application running, but this is it is running on a Docker container. Notice that the port has now been mapped to 8080 instead of 3000\.   
17. This is great\! We successfully created our local development environment. Next, we will move to the deployment of our application.

## Step 2: Set up the Build Environment

1. Your application has been successfully built in your local environment. Now, let’s move on to setting up an automated build environment using GitHub Actions.  
2. Create a workflow file in your project by creating .github/workflows folder. Then, add a file called workflow.yml (actually, you can choose any file name with the extension .yml) with the following content. 

| name: Run Tests and Build Docker on:   push:     branches:       \- main       \- master jobs:   test:     runs-on: ubuntu-latest     steps:       \- name: Checkout code         uses: actions/checkout@v4       \- name: Setup Node.js         uses: actions/setup-node@v4         with:           node-version: '18'           cache: 'npm'       \- name: Install dependencies         run: npm ci       \- name: Run tests         run: npm test       \- name: Upload coverage reports         uses: codecov/codecov-action@v3         if: always()         with:           files: ./coverage/lcov.info           fail\_ci\_if\_error: false |
| :---- |

   

3. Try to understand this workflow content. What does it do? Put the explanation below.  
   

|  |
| :---- |

   

4. Commit the change and push to the repository. Check that your action runs.  
5. Next, we will add another step to the workflow. Append this configuration to the workflow.yml file.  
   

|  docker:     runs-on: ubuntu-latest     needs: test     permissions:       contents: read       packages: write            steps:       \- name: Checkout code         uses: actions/checkout@v4       \- name: Set up Docker Buildx         uses: docker/setup-buildx-action@v3       \- name: Login to GitHub Container Registry         uses: docker/login-action@v3         with:           registry: ghcr.io           username: ${{ github.actor }}           password: ${{ secrets.GITHUB\_TOKEN }}       \- name: Extract metadata for Docker         id: meta         uses: docker/metadata-action@v5         with:           images: ghcr.io/${{ github.repository }}           tags: |             type=sha             type=ref,event=branch             latest       \- name: Build and push Docker image         uses: docker/build-push-action@v5         with:           context: .           push: true           tags: ${{ steps.meta.outputs.tags }}           labels: ${{ steps.meta.outputs.labels }}           cache-from: type=gha           cache-to: type=gha,mode=max |
| :---- |

   

6. Try to understand this additional step. What does it do? Put your explanation below.  
   

|  |
| :---- |

   

7. Configure your GitHub repository to allow the action to push the Docker image by going to Settings \> Actions \> General. Then, under the “Workflow Permissions” section, choose “Read and write permissions.”   
   ![][image5]  
8. Commit and push the changes. Then, make sure the Action successfully runs.  
9. Visit https://ghcr.io/\<YOUR GITHUB USERNAME\>/simple-todo-list to verify that the Docker image has been successfully pushed to the GitHub Container Registry. You should see the content like this.  
   ![][image6]  
10. Now, we will always have a new Docker image everytime the application is built.  
11. Try to make a few changes to the code (e.g., changing the page title in the index.html file) and make sure tha the whole pipeline works.

## Step 3: Deployment

1. Next, we will configure the deployment of our application to the cloud to make the application publicly available.  
2. In this exercise, we will use the Render Cloud Application Platform service ([https://render.com](https://render.com/)) since it offers a free-tier service so that we can try using it without any expenses.  
3. Start by visiting the [https://render.com/](https://render.com/) website and login using your GitHub account.  
   ![][image7]  
4. Once logged in, you’ll see your workspace.  
   ![][image8]  
5. Select “Deploy a Web Service” and select Git Provider. Select GitHub.  
   ![][image9]  
6. You may need to authorize Render to access your GitHub repository. You can do this by going to the Credentials menu on the right and select “Configure in GitHub.”   
   ![][image10]  
7. Then install Render in your GitHub Account.  
   ![][image11]  
8. Then, configure the Repository access to allow Render to access only the to-do list repository.  
   ![][image12]  
9. Once you have configured the Render permissions on your repository, the name of the repository should show up in the Render workspace. Select the repository.  
   ![][image13]  
10. Create a new project for this deployment.  
    ![][image14]  
    ![][image15]  
      
11. Select the Free tier for this deployment.  
    ![][image16]  
12. Once, everything is done. Click “Deploy Web Service.” Try to read the log.   
13. You will see that the Render service will retrieve the application’s code from your GitHub repository, build it, create a Docker image, and deploy it on their cloud. Wait until the deployment is complete.  
    ![][image17]  
14. When the deployment is complete by showing the “Live” symbol, you can visit your application via the link provided.  
    ![][image18]  
15. Play around with the deployed application to make sure that it works correctly.  
    ![][image19]  
16. Configure your Render project to automatically redeploy the application every time the GitHub Action workflow is successfully passed on your repository.  
    ![][image20]  
17. Make another small change in your application (e.g., modifying the title of the application in index.html). Then, push the changes to GitHub. Try to observe both GitHub Actions and Render workspace. You will see that Render will start deploying your application once the Action is finished and passed.  
18. Once the application is redeployed, access the application again to check that the new changes have been included in the deploy version.  
19. That’s great\! You have now configured the full pipeline from local development to deployment on the cloud. Next, let’s try adding a new feature and let the whole building and deployment pipeline work together for us.
